\begin_layout Subsection
Formation of chromosomal translocations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the development of chromosome banding microscopy, it has been known
 that the genetic material within cancerous cells is frequently disrupted
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mitelman2007"

\end_inset

.
 Chromosomal translocations involve the rearrangement of genetic material
 between non-homologous chromosomes through the formation and aberrant repair
 of two double strand breaks (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "DSB"
description "Double strand break"

\end_inset

DSBs).
 The resulting product can be a straight swap without any loss or gain of
 sequence (balanced translocation) or can result in deletions or gain of
 material (unbalanced translocation).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
DSB repair
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Double strand breaks can be caused by exogenous damage (ionizing radiation,
 free radicals) and endogenous damage (physiological programmed DSBs).
 As many as 1 million DNA lesions are formed per cell per day 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AlbertsLewisRaffRobertsWalter2007"

\end_inset

 and can be highly deleterious to the cell, casuing loss of genetic material,
 translocations and ultimately cell death if left unrepaired.
 Mammalian cells have an array of different DSB repair pathways that depend
 on the cellular context and type of lesion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Longhese2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Homologous recombination (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "HR"
description "Homologous recombination"

\end_inset

HR, Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DSB-repair"

\end_inset

B) repairs double strand breaks by using long regions of homology on undamaged
 sister chromatids or homologous chromosomes.
 HR is primarily active during cell replication and rarely leads to serious
 chromosomal rearrangements or translocations, although â€˜crossing-overâ€™
 can sometimes occur, whereby two sections of homologous chromosomes switch
 to their partner chromosomes (a process that is encouraged in meiosis with
 the formation of chiasmata).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Single strand annealing (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "SSA"
description "Single strand annealing"

\end_inset

SSA, Gif 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DSB-repair"

\end_inset

C) creates a short region of single stranded DNA at the site of the DSB
 which is used to search for regions of microhomology, usually repeat sequences
 in the same orientation.
 These regions anneal and any excess single stranded tails are removed to
 allow the nicks to be ligated.
 SSA is prone to introducing deletions into the genome, and can form chromosomal
 translocations if two sequences with similar repeat regions are nearby,
 and both suffer simultaneous DSBs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-homologous end joining (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "NHEJ"
description "Non-homologous end joining"

\end_inset

NHEJ, Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DSB-repair"

\end_inset

A) is a last resort for the cell, whereby any two adjacent DSBs are ligated,
 needing little or no sequence homology.
 This pathway is extremely prone to errors as it is capable of joining any
 two strands of DNA without knowledge of their identity.
\end_layout

