\begin_layout Subsection
Mixed lineage leukaemia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term leukaemia describes cancers of the blood or bone marrow, caused
 by an over-proliferation of one or more types of white blood cell.
 Leukaemia symptoms usually result from a drop in the production of other
 cell types in the bone marrow; additionally the leukaemic cells are usually
 unable to mount an immune response.
 Uncontrolled growth of different cell types gives different phenotypes,
 and there are a number of leukaemia subclasses that describe these.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acute Lymphoblastic Leukaemia (ALL) is a form of leukaemia defined by the
 uncontrolled proliferation of lymphoblasts, precursors to lymphocytes which
 differentiate into B cells, T cells and NK cells.
 ALL was estimated to account for approximately 12% of all leukaemia cases
 in the US in 2008 with around five and a half thousand cases occurring
 annually.
 ALL is the most common form of cancer in children aged under fourteen [47].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acute Myeloid Leukaemia (AML) is a cancer of the myeloid lineages of blood
 cells.
 AML was responsible for approximately 30% of all cases of leukaemia in
 the US for 2008, and has a higher mortality rate than ALL (66% and 27%
 mortality for AML and ALL, respectively) [47].
 The incidence of AML increases with age, the median age of AML diagnosis
 between 2002 and 2006 in the US was 67 years, and the median age of mortality
 was 72 [48].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the phenotypic typing of acute leukaemia is not always clear.
 Chromosomal translocations within band q23 of chromosome 11 have been implicate
d in both AML and ALL.
 The gene involved in this translocation was identified by Ziemin-van der
 Poel et al.
 in 1991 and named MLL (Myeloid/Lymphoid Leukaemia, or Mixed Lineage Leukaemia)
 [49].
 In 2002, Armstrong et al.
 showed that acute lymphoblastic leukaemias containing a translocation within
 the MLL gene have a unique expression profile that is different to ALL
 and AML, and suggests an origin within a less committed progenitor cell
 which can produce cells in both the myeloid and lymphoid cell lineages,
 giving a biphenotypic leukaemia (see Figure 8) [50].
 They stated that these leukaemias are substantially different from AML
 and ALL and deserve a new, distinct, class of leukaemia called Mixed Lineage
 Leukaemia (MLL).
 The leukaemic cells in MLL express cell surface antigens normally present
 on both myeloid and lymphoid cells, such as CD14 and CD19 [51].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The work by Armstrong et al adds to existing evidence suggesting that MLL
 and some cases of ALL and AML are initiated specifically within undifferentiate
d haematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) [52, 53].
 Haematopoietic stem cells are present within the CD34+ progenitor cell
 population, accounting for approximately 3% of normal human bone marrow
 and 0.3 to 0.5% of human cord blood mononuclear cells [44].
 They are long lived and capable of self-renewal, differentiating into lineage
 restricted progenitors and eventually mature terminally differentiated
 white blood cells (Figure 8).
 HSCs are necessary for the long term maintenance of the haematopoietic
 system and are commonly used to repopulate bone marrow after myeloablative
 therapy, as well as in the treatment of a number of other disorders such
 as autoimmune, cardiac and vascular diseases [54].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The initiation of these leukaemias within a stem cell population is in line
 with our increasing understanding of cancer stem cells, shown to be present
 in both leukaemias and solid tumours [55].
 Healthy HSCs are already capable of self-renewal, so may require less oncogenic
 events to become cancerous [56].
 The concept of a small pool of cancer stem-cells driving the large heterogeneou
s pool of cancer cells has many implications for how we treat cancer - these
 are the cells that must be targeted for the efficient and long lasting
 cure of cancer [56].
\end_layout

