\begin_layout Subsubsection
The MLL gene
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Translocations involving the MLL gene (also known as ALL-1, Htrx, HRX) on
 chromosome 11q23 are found in over 70% of infant leukaemias [58] and approximat
ely 10% of adult AML cases [51].
 Leukaemias with this translocation have a unique profile, and often a poor
 patient prognosis [59].
 As a result, a great deal of interest has been generated in the MLL gene
 and its translocation partners.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Homozygous (-/-) MLL mice knockouts are embryonic lethal, and are unable
 to produce haematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) [60].
 Heterozygous (+/-) knockouts display retarded growth and anaemia, as well
 as other haematopoietic abnormalities [61].
 Inducible mouse knockout models show that MLL is required for bone marrow
 maintenance, with bone marrow failure approximately three weeks after MLL
 deletion.
 Further to this, cells lacking MLL in MLL+/- chimeras are selectively lost
 from the bone marrow, consistent with a decrease in proliferation of myelo-eryt
hroid progenitors lacking MLL [62].
 However, haematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) lacking MLL are locked in ectopic
 cell cycle entry [62].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 87 documented MLL translocation partners of which 51 have been
 characterised at the molecular level [63].
 The five most frequent translocation partners, AF4, AF9, ENL, AF10 and
 AF6 account for approximately 80% of cases [63].
 Translocations within the MLL gene usually occur within an 8.3 kb region
 known as the breakpoint cluster region (bcr) [64].
 The bcr contains exons 5-11 as well as a number of repeat regions, notably
 8 direct Alu SINE repeats, 5 direct L1 and L2 LINE repeats and 2 MER elements,
 as well as a number of putative Topoisomerase II binding sites and a SAR/MAR
 [65] (see 7 - Abbreviations for full names).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A paper by Scharf et al.
