\begin_layout Subsubsection
The MLL protein
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MLL is a large protein, consisting of multiple domains.
 It has been shown too require assembly and targeting by multiple other
 proteins, such as WDR5, RBPB5 and ASH2L [69].
 MLL contains three N-terminal AT hooks, responsible for binding the minor
 groove of AT-rich DNA; a CxxC zinc finger domain homologous to that found
 in DNA methyltransferase I; a transcriptional activation (TA) domain which
 binds CREB binding protein, a histone acetyltransferase and a SET domain
 which can methylate the lysine 4 residue of histone 4 (H3K4).
 Several of these domains are also present within the Drosophila trithorax
 complex, such as the speckled nuclear localization domains and SET domain.
 It is thought that MLL binds DNA in a non-sequence-specific manner via
 its AT-hook domains [70] and zinc finger domain [71].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP) experiments pulling down chromatin
 fragments associated with MLL have shown interactions with 90% of elements
 occupied by RNAP II, including both promoters and intergenic regions [72,
 73].
 This demonstrates its role as a global regulator of gene expression, much
 like the Drosophila trithorax genes to which it shares homology.
\end_layout

